Note:
RISC-V Register Allocator - Architecture-Specific Constraint Resolution

Resolves RISC-V register allocation constraints after middle-end graph coloring.
RISC-V has 32 general-purpose registers (x0-x31) where x0 is hardwired to zero.

RISC-V is a clean three-address architecture with minimal constraints:
- x0 (zero) is always zero and writes are discarded
- x1 (ra) = return address
- x2 (sp) = stack pointer
- x3 (gp) = global pointer
- x4 (tp) = thread pointer
- x5-x7 (t0-t2) = temporaries (caller-saved)
- x8 (s0/fp) = saved/frame pointer (callee-saved)
- x9 (s1) = saved register (callee-saved)
- x10-x11 (a0-a1) = function args + return values
- x12-x17 (a2-a7) = function arguments
- x18-x27 (s2-s11) = saved registers (callee-saved)
- x28-x31 (t3-t6) = temporaries (caller-saved)

The clean three-address ISA means no two-address constraints, no implicit
register usage (unlike x86 IDIV), and no shift-count register requirements.

Dependencies:
- Imports LIR types for function, block, and instruction structures
- Imports LIRNodes for operand creation and instruction construction
- Imports memory/layout.runa for OWNED HEAP allocation (Tier 3)
- Imports list.runa for collection manipulation
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa" as LIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir_nodes.runa" as LIRNodes
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: RISC-V Register Constants (x0-x31)
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Zero register (hardwired to 0)
Constant REG_ZERO as Integer is 0    Note: x0  minus always zero

Note: Special registers
Constant REG_RA as Integer is 1      Note: x1  minus return address
Constant REG_SP as Integer is 2      Note: x2  minus stack pointer
Constant REG_GP as Integer is 3      Note: x3  minus global pointer
Constant REG_TP as Integer is 4      Note: x4  minus thread pointer

Note: Temporary registers (caller-saved)
Constant REG_T0 as Integer is 5      Note: x5
Constant REG_T1 as Integer is 6      Note: x6
Constant REG_T2 as Integer is 7      Note: x7

Note: Saved registers (callee-saved)
Constant REG_S0 as Integer is 8      Note: x8  minus also frame pointer (fp)
Constant REG_FP as Integer is 8      Note: x8  minus alias for s0
Constant REG_S1 as Integer is 9      Note: x9

Note: Argument/return registers
Constant REG_A0 as Integer is 10     Note: x10 minus arg 0 divided by return value 0
Constant REG_A1 as Integer is 11     Note: x11 minus arg 1 divided by return value 1
Constant REG_A2 as Integer is 12     Note: x12 minus arg 2
Constant REG_A3 as Integer is 13     Note: x13 minus arg 3
Constant REG_A4 as Integer is 14     Note: x14 minus arg 4
Constant REG_A5 as Integer is 15     Note: x15 minus arg 5
Constant REG_A6 as Integer is 16     Note: x16 minus arg 6
Constant REG_A7 as Integer is 17     Note: x17 minus arg 7

Note: Saved registers (callee-saved) continued
Constant REG_S2 as Integer is 18     Note: x18
Constant REG_S3 as Integer is 19     Note: x19
Constant REG_S4 as Integer is 20     Note: x20
Constant REG_S5 as Integer is 21     Note: x21
Constant REG_S6 as Integer is 22     Note: x22
Constant REG_S7 as Integer is 23     Note: x23
Constant REG_S8 as Integer is 24     Note: x24
Constant REG_S9 as Integer is 25     Note: x25
Constant REG_S10 as Integer is 26    Note: x26
Constant REG_S11 as Integer is 27    Note: x27

Note: Temporary registers (caller-saved) continued
Constant REG_T3 as Integer is 28     Note: x28
Constant REG_T4 as Integer is 29     Note: x29
Constant REG_T5 as Integer is 30     Note: x30
Constant REG_T6 as Integer is 31     Note: x31

Note: Total GPRs
Constant RISCV_GPR_COUNT as Integer is 32
Constant RISCV_ALLOCATABLE_COUNT as Integer is 27
Note: Allocatable: x5-x31 - x8(fp if used) = 26 or 27 registers

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LIR Opcode Constants (mirrored from LIR)
Note: ============================================================================

Constant OP_MOV as Integer is 30001
Constant OP_ADD as Integer is 30100
Constant OP_SUB as Integer is 30101
Constant OP_IMUL as Integer is 30102
Constant OP_IDIV as Integer is 30103
Constant OP_MUL as Integer is 30104
Constant OP_DIV as Integer is 30105
Constant OP_AND as Integer is 30200
Constant OP_OR as Integer is 30201
Constant OP_XOR as Integer is 30202
Constant OP_SHL as Integer is 30300
Constant OP_SHR as Integer is 30301
Constant OP_SAR as Integer is 30302
Constant OP_CALL as Integer is 30520

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constraint Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
RISC-V has the cleanest ISA design of the three architectures, with very
few register constraints:

1. No two-address form - all instructions are three-address (rd, rs1, rs2)
2. No implicit register usage - DIVU/DIVW uses explicit operands (unlike x86 IDIV)
3. No shift-count register - shift amount can be any register or immediate
4. Calling convention: a0-a7 for arguments, a0-a1 for return values
5. ra (x1) for return address (must be saved by callee if it makes calls)

The only constraints are:
- CONSTRAINT_CALL_ARGS: arguments must be in a0-a7 before calls
- CONSTRAINT_CALL_RETURN: return value is in a0 after calls
- CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG: for specific calling convention needs
@End Reasoning

Constant CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG as Integer is 1
Constant CONSTRAINT_CLOBBER as Integer is 2
Constant CONSTRAINT_CALL_ARGS as Integer is 3
Constant CONSTRAINT_CALL_RETURN as Integer is 4

Note: ============================================================================
Note: RISCVAllocConstraint Type Definition
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "RISCVAllocConstraint":
    instruction_index as Integer
    constraint_type as Integer
    required_register as Integer
    operand_index as Integer
    block_index as Integer
End Type

Note: Size: 5 fields * 8 bytes = 40 bytes per RISCVAllocConstraint

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Register Information Queries
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "is_allocatable_register" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns 1 if the register is available for general allocation
    Note: x0 (zero), x1 (ra), x2 (sp), x3 (gp), x4 (tp) are reserved
    If reg_id is less than or equal to 4:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg_id is greater than 31:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "is_callee_saved" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: RISC-V calling convention: s0-s11 (x8-x9, x18-x27) are callee-saved
    If reg_id is 8:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg_id is 9:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg_id is greater than or equal to 18:
        If reg_id is less than or equal to 27:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_caller_saved" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Caller-saved: t0-t6 (x5-x7, x28-x31), a0-a7 (x10-x17), ra (x1)
    If reg_id is 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg_id is greater than or equal to 5:
        If reg_id is less than or equal to 7:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If reg_id is greater than or equal to 10:
        If reg_id is less than or equal to 17:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If reg_id is greater than or equal to 28:
        If reg_id is less than or equal to 31:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_argument_register" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: a0-a7 (x10-x17) are used for up to 8 integer arguments
    If reg_id is greater than or equal to 10:
        If reg_id is less than or equal to 17:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "get_allocatable_registers" returns Integer:
    Note: Returns a List of allocatable register IDs for RISC-V
    Note: Order: temporaries first, then argument regs, then saved regs
    Let regs be List.list_create(32)
    If regs is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Temporary registers (no save/restore cost, caller-saved)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_T0)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_T1)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_T2)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_T3)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_T4)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_T5)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_T6)

    Note: Argument registers (caller-saved)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_A0)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_A1)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_A2)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_A3)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_A4)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_A5)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_A6)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_A7)

    Note: Saved registers (callee-saved, require save/restore)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_S1)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_S2)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_S3)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_S4)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_S5)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_S6)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_S7)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_S8)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_S9)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_S10)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_S11)

    Note: s0/fp last (often used as frame pointer)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_S0)

    Return regs
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Virtual-to-Physical Register Mapping
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "map_virtual_to_physical" that takes virtual_reg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Maps LIR virtual register IDs to RISC-V physical registers
    Note: Starts with temporaries, then argument regs, then saved regs
    Note: Returns -1 if spill is required
    If virtual_reg is less than 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If

    Note: First 7 virtual regs -> temporaries t0-t6
    If virtual_reg is less than or equal to 6:
        If virtual_reg is less than or equal to 2:
            Return REG_T0 plus virtual_reg
        End If
        Return REG_T3 plus (virtual_reg minus 3)
    End If

    Note: Next 8 virtual regs -> argument registers a0-a7
    If virtual_reg is less than or equal to 14:
        Return REG_A0 plus (virtual_reg minus 7)
    End If

    Note: Next 12 virtual regs -> saved registers s0-s11
    If virtual_reg is less than or equal to 26:
        Let s_index be virtual_reg minus 15
        If s_index is 0:
            Return REG_S0
        End If
        If s_index is 1:
            Return REG_S1
        End If
        Return REG_S2 plus (s_index minus 2)
    End If

    Note: Virtual register exceeds physical register count; needs spill
    Return 0 minus 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constraint Collection
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
RISC-V has remarkably few constraints due to its clean three-address design:

1. All arithmetic/logic/shift instructions: rd, rs1, rs2 - no constraints
2. DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU: rd, rs1, rs2 - no implicit registers (unlike x86)
3. MUL/MULH/MULHU: rd, rs1, rs2 - no constraints
4. Shifts: rd, rs1, rs2 or rd, rs1, shamt - no CL requirement

The only constraints come from the calling convention:
- Before CALL (jalr/jal): arguments must be placed in a0-a7
- After CALL: return value is in a0

This collector only emits constraints for CALL instructions.
@End Reasoning

Process called "collect_riscv_constraints" that takes lir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_function is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let constraints be List.list_create(16)
    If constraints is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let blocks be __load(lir_function, 32)
    Let block_count be __load(lir_function, 40)

    If blocks is 0:
        Return constraints
    End If
    If block_count is 0:
        Return constraints
    End If

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be List.list_get(blocks, b)
        If block is not 0:
            Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
            Let inst_count be __load(block, 24)

            If instructions is not 0:
                Let i be 0
                While i is less than inst_count:
                    Let instruction be List.list_get(instructions, i)
                    If instruction is not 0:
                        Let opcode be __load(instruction, 0)

                        Note: CALL: arguments must be in a0-a7, return in a0
                        If opcode is OP_CALL:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_CALL_ARGS, REG_A0, 1, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set i to i plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return constraints
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Internal Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_constraint" that takes inst_idx as Integer, ctype as Integer, req_reg as Integer, op_idx as Integer, blk_idx as Integer returns Integer:
    Let c be Layout.allocate(40)
    If c is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    __store(c, 0, inst_idx)
    __store(c, 8, ctype)
    __store(c, 16, req_reg)
    __store(c, 24, op_idx)
    __store(c, 32, blk_idx)
    Return c
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Register Copy Insertion
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "insert_register_copy" that takes block as Integer, before_index as Integer, dest_reg as Integer, src_reg as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If dest_reg is src_reg:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let mov_instruction be LIRNodes.create_lir_instruction(OP_MOV)
    If mov_instruction is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let dest_operand be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(dest_reg, size)
    If dest_operand is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let src_operand be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(src_reg, size)
    If src_operand is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    __store(mov_instruction, 8, dest_operand)
    __store(mov_instruction, 16, src_operand)
    __store(mov_instruction, 48, block)

    Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
    If instructions is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    List.list_insert_at(instructions, before_index, mov_instruction)

    Let inst_count be __load(block, 24)
    __store(block, 24, inst_count plus 1)

    Let new_count be inst_count plus 1
    Let idx be before_index
    While idx is less than new_count:
        Let inst be List.list_get(instructions, idx)
        If inst is not 0:
            __store(inst, 64, idx)
        End If
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Complete Constraint Resolution Pass
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
RISC-V constraint resolution is minimal compared to x86.
The main work is ensuring calling convention compliance:
1. Move arguments to a0-a7 before call instructions
2. Move return value from a0 to destination after call instructions
3. No two-address fixups needed (three-address ISA)
4. No implicit register fixups needed (clean register usage)
@End Reasoning

Process called "resolve_riscv_constraints" that takes lir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_function is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let constraints be collect_riscv_constraints(lir_function)
    If constraints is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let constraint_count be List.list_length(constraints)
    If constraint_count is 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Process constraints in reverse order
    Let ci be constraint_count minus 1
    While ci is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let constraint be List.list_get(constraints, ci)
        If constraint is not 0:
            Let inst_idx be __load(constraint, 0)
            Let ctype be __load(constraint, 8)
            Let blk_idx be __load(constraint, 32)

            Let blocks be __load(lir_function, 32)
            Let block be List.list_get(blocks, blk_idx)
            If block is not 0:
                Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
                Let instruction be List.list_get(instructions, inst_idx)
                If instruction is not 0:
                    If ctype is CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG:
                        Let req_reg be __load(constraint, 16)
                        Let op_idx be __load(constraint, 24)
                        handle_fixed_reg_constraint(instruction, block, inst_idx, req_reg, op_idx)
                    End If
                    If ctype is CONSTRAINT_CALL_ARGS:
                        handle_call_args_constraint(lir_function, instruction, block, inst_idx)
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set ci to ci minus 1
    End While

    Note: Coalesce redundant moves
    coalesce_moves(lir_function)

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Fixed Register Constraint Handler
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "handle_fixed_reg_constraint" that takes instruction as Integer, block as Integer, inst_index as Integer, required_reg as Integer, operand_index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let operand_offset be 16 plus (operand_index multiplied by 8)
    If operand_index is 0:
        Set operand_offset to 8
    End If

    Let operand_ptr be __load(instruction, operand_offset)
    If operand_ptr is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let op_type be __load(operand_ptr, 0)
    If op_type is not 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_reg be __load(operand_ptr, 8)
    If current_reg is required_reg:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let success be insert_register_copy(block, inst_index, required_reg, current_reg, 8)
    If success is 1:
        __store(operand_ptr, 8, required_reg)
    End If
    Return success
End Process

Process called "handle_call_args_constraint" that takes lir_function as Integer, instruction as Integer, block as Integer, inst_index as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Ensures call arguments are in a0-a7 registers
    Note: Higher-level instruction selection handles argument placement
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Move Coalescing
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "coalesce_moves" that takes lir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_function is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let blocks be __load(lir_function, 32)
    Let block_count be __load(lir_function, 40)
    If blocks is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let removed_count be 0
    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be List.list_get(blocks, b)
        If block is not 0:
            Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
            Let inst_count be __load(block, 24)
            If instructions is not 0:
                Let i be inst_count minus 1
                While i is greater than or equal to 0:
                    Let inst be List.list_get(instructions, i)
                    If inst is not 0:
                        Let opcode be __load(inst, 0)
                        If opcode is OP_MOV:
                            Let result_ptr be __load(inst, 8)
                            Let operand1_ptr be __load(inst, 16)
                            If result_ptr is not 0:
                                If operand1_ptr is not 0:
                                    Let r_type be __load(result_ptr, 0)
                                    Let o_type be __load(operand1_ptr, 0)
                                    If r_type is 1:
                                        If o_type is 1:
                                            Let r_reg be __load(result_ptr, 8)
                                            Let o_reg be __load(operand1_ptr, 8)
                                            If r_reg is o_reg:
                                                List.list_remove_at(instructions, i)
                                                Let new_count be __load(block, 24)
                                                __store(block, 24, new_count minus 1)
                                                Set removed_count to removed_count plus 1
                                            End If
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set i to i minus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return removed_count
End Process
